A few concrete notes for you before you switch over:

Your instinct on DI and tests is good, but the order should be:
	•	runtime proof first
	•	then DI seams
	•	then tests around those seams

For this repo, the first useful seams will likely be:
	•	pipe message handling
	•	request/response contracts
	•	tool dispatch abstraction
	•	VS service abstraction

The easiest early tests will likely be:
	•	shared contract serialization/deserialization
	•	tool request validation
	•	IPC message framing/parsing
	•	MCP-server-side dispatch behavior with mocked VS-facing interfaces

I would avoid trying to make the Visual Studio package itself deeply unit-testable in the first pass. Better to isolate the VS-dependent parts behind interfaces and test everything around them.

On MEF: acceptable on the VSIX side if it fits naturally with Visual Studio composition, but I would not force MEF across the whole solution just for purity. For the out-of-process server and shared logic, plain constructor injection is usually simpler.


