That maps exactly to the failure mode I’d expect here.

What bit you in EFCorePowerTools is the same class of risk in this project: UI-owned orchestration plus background work that sometimes re-enters the UI thread in the wrong place. In a VSIX/WPF setup, that turns into deadlocks, hangs, or brittle “works on my machine” timing bugs fast.

For VS MCP Bridge, I’d treat this as an architectural constraint now, not a cleanup item later.

What to do with that lesson

The safest rule is:

keep the UI thin, and keep it out of the request pipeline as much as possible.

In practice:
	•	The tool window should display state, logs, approvals, and results.
	•	It should not own orchestration.
	•	The VSIX service layer should coordinate Visual Studio interactions.
	•	Anything not requiring Visual Studio APIs should stay off the UI thread and ideally outside the WPF layer entirely.

The deadlock pattern to avoid

The dangerous shape is:
	1.	background work starts
	2.	it needs something from Visual Studio/WPF
	3.	it switches to UI thread
	4.	UI thread is waiting on the background task
	5.	deadlock

So in this repo, avoid all of these patterns:
	•	.Result
	•	.Wait()
	•	synchronous blocking on async work
	•	UI code calling into services that later marshal back to UI thread while the UI is blocked
	•	background services raising callbacks that synchronously update WPF controls

The design rule I’d hand to Codex later

Use this rule:

only the smallest possible Visual Studio-facing boundary may switch to the main thread, and only for the shortest possible duration.

That means:
	•	collect VS state on UI thread only when required
	•	immediately copy the needed data into plain typed models
	•	return to background processing
	•	never carry WPF/VS objects across that boundary

That one rule will save you a lot of pain.

For your current codebase

Given what you’re already seeing, I would bias toward these seams once runtime validation is done:

1. Separate UI from services

Create a service boundary like:
	•	IVsContextService
	•	IApprovalService
	•	ILogService
	•	IPipeHostService

The tool window talks to interfaces, not directly to pipe/runtime code.

2. Make the tool window passive

The WPF window should:
	•	bind to state
	•	issue simple commands
	•	render logs/approvals

It should not:
	•	manage pipe lifecycle
	•	manage request dispatch
	•	own threading decisions

3. Isolate main-thread-only code

Anything requiring Visual Studio thread affinity should be in one narrow layer, something like:
	•	VsThreadBoundService
	•	VsShellService
	•	VsDocumentService

That layer can explicitly switch to main thread, gather what it needs, and get out.

4. Keep shared models POCO-only

No WPF types, no DTE objects, no VS SDK types in shared contracts.

That keeps:
	•	serialization easy
	•	tests easy
	•	collaboration easier

Unit-test implications

Your EFCorePowerTools experience is a strong signal that you should establish tests around the non-UI pipeline first.

Best early test targets here:
	•	pipe message framing/parsing
	•	request/response DTOs
	•	tool dispatch
	•	diff proposal logic
	•	policy checks
	•	path guardrails

Avoid trying to unit test WPF behavior directly in the first pass. Instead, test the logic behind it.

About DI / MEF in light of this

Your reason for DI is strong here, because it helps break the exact hard dependencies that caused pain before.

My recommendation:
	•	constructor injection for shared/server/testable code
	•	narrow VSIX-facing interfaces for Visual Studio-dependent services
	•	MEF only where Visual Studio composition naturally benefits from it

I would not let MEF become the architecture. Use it as integration glue if needed, not as the center of everything.

Threading rule of thumb for this repo

A good discipline for contributors would be:
	•	default to background thread
	•	switch to main thread only inside Visual Studio-facing service methods
	•	never block the UI waiting for background work
	•	never let WPF controls directly trigger deep async orchestration

What this means for your next phase

You’re still right to do runtime validation first.

But once that’s green, your first structural improvement should probably be:

move pipe lifecycle and request handling out of WPF/tool-window code and behind interfaces.

That will give you:
	•	fewer UI thread hazards
	•	easier tests
	•	easier contributor collaboration
	•	less coupling


